        <h3>How many stars are there?</h3>
        In our solar system there is only one star which is our very own Sun.<br>
        There has been debate of a second star called Nemesis that exists on the edge of our solar system that is theorized to appear every 32 million years but this has yet to be proven.[<a href="https://www.planetsforkids.org/how-many-stars-are-in-the-solar-system.html">REF</a>]<br>
        The current estimate for the number of stars in our own Milky Way galaxy varies wildly from about 1 billion to 4 billion.[<a href="https://asd.gsfc.nasa.gov/blueshift/index.php/2015/07/22/how-many-stars-in-the-milky-way/">REF</a>]<br>
        The current estimate for the amount of stars in the universe is around 1 septillion/quadrillion but there is most likely many more than this.[<a href="https://www.space.com/26078-how-many-stars-are-there.html">REF</a>]
        <span class="tooltipNew">
            [*]<br>
            <span class="tooltiptextNew">
                For perspective 1 septillion/quadrillion can also be written as 1,000,000,000,000,000,000,000,000.
            </span>
        </span><br />
        This is because it is very difficult to accurately count or estimate the amount of stars our galaxy or universe has due to the large amount of them.

