        <h3>What are binary/multistar systems?</h3>
        All information in this section is from [<a href="https://www.universetoday.com/132154/multiple-star-systems/">HERE</a>] unless specified.<br><br>
        <div class="col-lg-4">

            These happen when two or more stars orbit each other.<br>
            Around ⅓ of the star systems in the Milky way are multi star systems.<br>
            Can be anywhere from two stars in a system to seven stars.<br>
            Stars that are close enough can share material with one another.<br>
            If one of the stars is a red giant it can either pass material to its partner or engulf it depending on the size of the red giant and the distance between the stars.
            Binary neutron stars will eventually collide and form black holes.<br>
            A special kind of system is a Thorne-Zytkow object which is a red giant that is near binary neutron stars.
            The neutron stars will go into the red giant either turning into a black hole and absorbing the red giant or becoming a larger neutron star.
            <span class="tooltipNew">
