    <div>
        <h3>Lifecycle of a Star</h3>
        All information in this section is from [<a href="https://www.universetoday.com/24299/types-of-stars/amp/">HERE</a>] unless specified.<br>
        The image below is a diagram of the lifecyle of stars. <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Star_Life_Cycle_Chart.jpg">Source</a><br><br>

        An average sized star will follow this cycle.
        <ol>
            <li>It will eventually run out of hydrogen in its core and start burning hydrogen on the outside of the star.</li>
            <li>The star will expand massively into a red giant.</li>
            <li>The star will still contain many of the same elements like hydrogen and helium but eventually burn through them.</li>
            <li>When the red giant runs out of fuel it will condense into a white dwarf.</li>
            <li>This is made up of heavier elements that the star can no longer use as fuel due to its size.</li>
        </ol>

        A much larger sized star will follow this cycle.
        <ol>
            <li>It will eventually turn into a red giant.</li>
            <li>The star will then release a massive supernova explosion leaving behind a neutron star.</li>
            <li>These stars are mostly made up of neutrons because protons and electrons have been crushed into neutrons due to the intense gravity they have.</li>
            <li>If the star is massive enough the neutron star may condense itself into a black hole.</li>
        </ol>

        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/47/Star_Life_Cycle_Chart.jpg/1024px-Star_Life_Cycle_Chart.jpg" alt="A diagram of a star's lifecylce" />


    </div>
